BIRDWATCHER¶

This notebook takes you through the process of training and finetuning an image classifier on a self-curated dataset of 10 of the most-common birds found in Texas.
We'll use the pytorch deep learning library to build and train the model. Given that the dataset has only a few hundred instances of each category, we'll use transfer learning to build a classifier. Transfer Learning is a useful technique in deep learning where we can use a model trained on a dataset that is different from our particular dataset, but is similar enough that the knowledge acquired by the model during its training can be reused for our task with a little fine-tuning.

Transfer Learning is specially useful when there aren't enough samples in a dataset to build a model from scratch or there aren't enough computational resources available to train from scratch complex models such as ResNet101. Transfer Learning proves to be an efficient and economic solution in such cases.

Separating train, test and validation images¶

We split the image dataset such that 30% of the images are used for test set, 59.5% of the images are used for training and the remaining for the validation set.

In [4]:
test_dir = './test/'
train_dir = './train'
train_ratio = 0.74
_, dirs, _ = next(os.walk(train_dir))
images_per_class = np.zeros(10) # 10 is number of classes
for i in range(10):
    path = os.path.join(train_dir,dirs[i])
    files = np.asarray(os.listdir(path))
    images_per_class[i] = len(files)
    
val_counter = np.round(images_per_class * (1-train_ratio))

# transfer files
for i in range(10):
    source_path = os.path.join(train_dir, dirs[i])
    dest_path = os.path.join(test_dir, dirs[i])
    if not os.path.exists(dest_path):
        os.makedirs(dest_path)
    files = np.asarray(os.listdir(source_path))
    for j in range(int(val_counter[i])):
        dst = os.path.join(dest_path, files[j])
        src = os.path.join(source_path, files[j])
        shutil.move(src,dst)

Data Augmentations¶

The dataset curated by us has images of different of shapes. Before feeding images into the neural network its best to have the input standardized and normalized. Following transformations are applied to the images before feeding them into the network - images are resized to 256 x 256 x 3, randomly flipped along the vertical axis and normalized.

In [6]:
data_transforms = {
    'train': transforms.Compose([
        transforms.Resize((256,256)),
#         transforms.RandomResizedCrop(224),
        transforms.RandomHorizontalFlip(),
        transforms.ToTensor(),
        transforms.Normalize([0.485, 0.456, 0.406], [0.229, 0.224, 0.225])
    ]),
    'val': transforms.Compose([
        transforms.Resize((256,256)),
        transforms.ToTensor(),
        transforms.Normalize([0.485, 0.456, 0.406], [0.229, 0.224, 0.225])
    ]),
    'test': transforms.Compose([
        transforms.Resize((256,256)),
        transforms.ToTensor()
    ]),
}

def imshow(inp, title=None):
    """Imshow for Tensor."""
    inp = inp.numpy().transpose((1, 2, 0))
    mean = np.array([0.485, 0.456, 0.406])
    std = np.array([0.229, 0.224, 0.225])
    inp = std * inp + mean
    inp = np.clip(inp, 0, 1)
    fig = plt.figure(figsize=(8,8))
    plt.grid(False)
    plt.imshow(inp)
    if title is not None:
        plt.title(title)

We'll be using the following metrics to evaluate our models' performances - accuracy, f1-score, precision, recall and confusion matrix. The following cell initializes each of these metrics for training and validation datasets.

In [12]:
train_metrics = {}
val_metrics = {}

train_metrics['accuracy'] = []
train_metrics['f1-score'] = []
train_metrics['precision'] = []
train_metrics['recall'] = []

val_metrics['accuracy'] = []
val_metrics['f1-score'] = []
val_metrics['precision'] = []
val_metrics['recall'] = []

Model Training¶

The following function specifies how model training is performed. At the beginning of each epoch, all losses and predictions are reinitialized. For every batch of images in the training set, the model predicts the classes and the losses accumulated are backward propagated into the network. After each epoch, the model is run on the validation set and the performances are noted.

In [13]:
def train_model(model, criterion, optimizer, num_epochs=25):
    
    start_time = time.time()

    best_model = copy.deepcopy(model.state_dict())
    best_val_acc = 0.0
    

    for epoch in tqdm(range(num_epochs)):

        model.train()  # Set model to training mode
        running_loss = 0.0
        running_corrects = 0
        y_true = []
        y_pred = []
        
        # Iterate over data.
        for inputs, labels in dataloaders['train']:
            inputs = inputs.to(device)
            labels = labels.to(device)

            # zero the parameter gradients
            optimizer.zero_grad()

            outputs = model(inputs)
            _, preds = torch.max(outputs, 1)
            loss = criterion(outputs, labels)

            loss.backward()
            optimizer.step()

            # statistics
            running_loss += loss.item() * inputs.size(0)
            running_corrects += torch.sum(preds == labels.data)
            
            y_true += labels.data.cpu()
            y_pred += preds.cpu()
            
        train_metrics['accuracy'].append(accuracy_score(y_true, y_pred))
        train_metrics['f1-score'].append(f1_score(y_true, y_pred, average="macro"))
        train_metrics['precision'].append(precision_score(y_true, y_pred, average="macro"))
        train_metrics['recall'].append(recall_score(y_true, y_pred, average="macro"))
        
        print('Train Accuracy: {}'.format(train_metrics['accuracy'][-1]))
        print('Train F1: {}'.format(train_metrics['f1-score'][-1]))
        print('Train Precision: {}'.format(train_metrics['precision'][-1]))
        print('Train Recall: {}'.format(train_metrics['recall'][-1]))
            
       
        model.eval()   # Set model to evaluate mode

        running_loss = 0.0
        running_corrects = 0
        y_true = []
        y_pred = []
        
        # Iterate over data.
        for inputs, labels in dataloaders['val']:
            inputs = inputs.to(device)
            labels = labels.to(device)

            outputs = model(inputs)
            _, preds = torch.max(outputs, 1)
            loss = criterion(outputs, labels)

            # statistics
            running_loss += loss.item() * inputs.size(0)
            running_corrects += torch.sum(preds == labels.data)
            
            y_true += labels.data.cpu()
            y_pred += preds.cpu()
        
        val_metrics['accuracy'].append(accuracy_score(y_true, y_pred))
        val_metrics['f1-score'].append(f1_score(y_true, y_pred, average="macro"))
        val_metrics['precision'].append(precision_score(y_true, y_pred, average="macro"))
        val_metrics['recall'].append(recall_score(y_true, y_pred, average="macro"))
        
        print('Val Accuracy: {}'.format(val_metrics['accuracy'][-1]))
        print('Val F1: {}'.format(val_metrics['f1-score'][-1]))
        print('Val Precision: {}'.format(val_metrics['precision'][-1]))
        print('Val Recall: {}'.format(val_metrics['recall'][-1]))
            
        if val_metrics['accuracy'][-1] > best_val_acc:
            best_val_acc = val_metrics['accuracy'][-1]
            best_model = copy.deepcopy(model.state_dict())

    time_elapsed = time.time() - start_time
    print(f'Training complete in {time_elapsed // 60:.0f}m {time_elapsed % 60:.0f}s')
    print(f'Best val Acc: {best_val_acc:4f}')

    # load best model weights
    model.load_state_dict(best_model)
    return model

Freezing some layers of the model¶

It is well known that convolutional neural networks learn more general features that are broadly applicable to image classfication in the earlier layers. Features such as corners, color blobs, edges etc. are learned in these layers. And as we move towards the further layers, the features learned become more complex and more specific to the dataset. It is often beneficial to freeze some of the layers at the beginning of the network to retain the basic knowledge applciable to general image classification. In our case, after some trial and error, it was found that freezing the first 30 layers of the network allowed the accuracy and the other metrics to converge faster.

In [14]:
model_ft = models.resnet18(pretrained=True)

i=0
for param in model_ft.parameters():
    if(i>30):
        param.requires_grad = True
    i += 1
    param.requires_grad = False
    
num_ftrs = model_ft.fc.in_features
model_ft.fc = nn.Linear(num_ftrs, len(class_names))
model_ft = model_ft.to(device)

Performance on the test set¶
Now that our model is trained, let's see how it performs on data it has never seen before. Our model's performance on the test set gives us an idea about how the model will perform once deployed in a real-world application.











In [19]:



     


model_ft.eval()   # Set model to evaluate mode

running_loss = 0.0
running_corrects = 0
y_true = []
y_pred = []

# Iterate over data.
for inputs, labels in tqdm(dataloaders['test']):
    inputs = inputs.to(device)
    labels = labels.to(device)

    outputs = model_ft(inputs)
    _, preds = torch.max(outputs, 1)
    loss = criterion(outputs, labels)

    # statistics
    running_loss += loss.item() * inputs.size(0)
    running_corrects += torch.sum(preds == labels.data)

    y_true += labels.data.cpu()
    y_pred += preds.cpu()

val_acc = accuracy_score(y_true, y_pred)

print('Test Accuracy: {}'.format(val_acc))
print('Test F1: {}'.format(f1_score(y_true, y_pred, average="macro")))
print('Test Precision: {}'.format(precision_score(y_true, y_pred, average="macro")))
print('Test Recall: {}'.format(recall_score(y_true, y_pred, average="macro")))

def plot_confusion_matrix(cm, classes, name, normalize=True, title='Confusion matrix', cmap=plt.cm.Blues):

    """

    This function prints and plots the confusion matrix.

    Normalization can be applied by setting `normalize=True`.

    """

    plt.figure(figsize=(10,10))


    plt.imshow(cm, interpolation='nearest', cmap=cmap)

    plt.title(title)

    plt.colorbar()


    tick_marks = np.arange(len(classes))

    plt.xticks(tick_marks, classes, rotation=45)

    plt.yticks(tick_marks, classes)


    if normalize:

        cm = cm.astype('float') / cm.sum(axis=1)[:, np.newaxis]

        cm = np.around(cm, decimals=2)

        cm[np.isnan(cm)] = 0.0

        print("Normalized confusion matrix")

    else:

        print('Confusion matrix, without normalization')

    thresh = cm.max() / 2.

    for i, j in itertools.product(range(cm.shape[0]), range(cm.shape[1])):

        plt.text(j, i, cm[i, j],

                 horizontalalignment="center",

                 color="white" if cm[i, j] > thresh else "black")

    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.grid(b=None)
    plt.ylabel('True label')

    plt.xlabel('Predicted label')
    plt.savefig(f'./confusion_matrix_{name}.png')
